    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Olympics? No Thanks</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Andrew Dier letter, commenting on Sept 12 article, opposes staging 2008 Summer Olympics in New York City</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Plan to Put Olympics in New York Draws Fire'' (news article, Sept. 12): New York City is the greatest city in the world. What do we have to prove to the world by staging an Olympics?</p>
        <p>We don't want the clogged streets, overcrowded subways and trains and other inconveniences that this corporate-sponsored circus will bring. We don't want millions of our public dollars spent on building Olympic stadiums and sites for synchronized swimming, rhythmic gymnastics and the like.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Plan to Put Olympics in New York Draws Fire'' (news article, Sept. 12): New York City is the greatest city in the world. What do we have to prove to the world by staging an Olympics?</p>
        <p>We don't want the clogged streets, overcrowded subways and trains and other inconveniences that this corporate-sponsored circus will bring. We don't want millions of our public dollars spent on building Olympic stadiums and sites for synchronized swimming, rhythmic gymnastics and the like.</p>
        <p>Let another city that needs the spotlight and wants the headache have them both.</p>
        <p>ANDREW DIER  New York, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
